  "prompt": "What is the difference between JDK and SDK in Java?",
  "response": "Let me explain the differences between JDK and SDK in Java:\n\nJDK (Java Development Kit):\n1. Specifically for Java programming\n2. Contains tools for developing Java applications\n3. Includes:\n   - Java compiler (javac)\n   - Java Runtime Environment (JRE)\n   - Development tools\n   - Java APIs\n4. Used exclusively for Java development\n5. Specific to Java language\n\nSDK (Software Development Kit):\n1. A more general term for a collection of development tools\n2. Can be for any programming language or platform\n3. Includes:\n   - Compiler\n   - Debugger\n   - Documentation\n   - Code samples\n   - Libraries\n4. Can be used for multiple programming languages\n5. Broader in scope\n\nExample:\n- Java JDK is a specific type of SDK for Java\n- Android SDK is used for Android app development\n- iOS SDK is used for iOS app development\n\nKey Differences:\n- JDK is Java-specific\n- SDK is a broader concept that can include JDK as a type of SDK\n\nPractical Comparison:\n```\n// JDK is a type of SDK\nJDK = Specialized SDK for Java Development\nSDK = Broader development toolkit for various platforms\n```\n\nIn essence, all JDKs are SDKs, but not all SDKs are JDKs.",
